TY  - JOUR
AU  - Schindler, David
AU  - Westcott, Mark
T1  - Shocking Racial Attitudes: Black G.I.s in Europe
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdaa039
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 88
IS  - 1
SP  - 489
EP  - 520
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Can attitudes towards minorities, an important cultural trait, be changed? We show that the presence of African American soldiers in the UK during World War II reduced anti-minority prejudice, a result of the positive interactions which took place between soldiers and the local population. The change has been persistent: in locations in which more African American soldiers were posted there are fewer members of and voters for the UK’s leading far-right party, less implicit bias against blacks and fewer individuals professing racial prejudice, all measured around 2010. Our results point towards intergenerational transmission from parents to children as the most likely explanation.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdaa039
ER  - 



